   	<li class="clear" id="comment-119640">
    	<div class="comment byuser comment-author-maymay bypostauthor odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 clear">
	   		<div class="col140">
	   				   			<p>by <strong><a href='http://maybemaimed.com/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>maymay</a></strong></p>
	   			<p><strong>01 Mar 2011</strong> at <a href="#comment-119640">20:47</a></p>
	   				   				   		</div>
	   		
	   		<div class="col460 clear">
	       		<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/39ece444504f8db7c07c1a6c42345a82?s=50&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D50&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-50 photo' height='50' width='50' />	   				   			<p>Okay, finally I have a moment to get back into this discussion. Sorry for the delay, everyone. And thanks for your <em>amazing</em> commentary thus far.</p>
<p>First, <a href="#comment-117490" rel="nofollow">SnowdropExplodes</a> made a point I think is worth mentioning but also highlights either my own explanatory failure or a miscommunication:</p>
<blockquote cite="#comment-117490"><p>there’s another self/other gaze element that can be identified  […] there’s a scale also between “empathy” and “embodiment” to be considered.</p></blockquote>
<p>So, I&#8217;d say no, that&#8217;s not quite right. What you seem (at least to me) to be saying is that there are multiple ways of looking at the same situation. This does not actually result in another element, merely a different perspective on the same dataset. When you say, for instance,</p>
<blockquote cite="#comment-117490"><p> the difference between “I enjoy seeing that he is enjoying doing these sex acts” and “I would really enjoy being him doing these sex acts”</p></blockquote>
<p>all you&#8217;re really identifying is that there are multiple angles of access from which you can relate to the gaze itself. In film theory, this is known as a &#8220;double gaze.&#8221; It comes up in <a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=7ADDj41AVSUC&#038;lpg=PA133&#038;dq=%22double%20gaze%22&#038;pg=PA133#v=onepage&#038;q=%22double%20gaze%22&#038;f=false" rel="nofollow">discussions of nationalism</a>, as well as in <a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=x4fLaCLD11MC&#038;lpg=PA204&#038;ots=93AftxMacX&#038;dq=%22double%20gaze%22%20cinema&#038;pg=PA204#v=onepage&#038;q=%22double%20gaze%22%20cinema&#038;f=false" rel="nofollow">gendered media study</a>. But again, I think it is a mistake to theorize that this is a new degree of granularity, rather than a different vantage point on the same &#8220;concrete&#8221; event.</p>
<p>In other words, it sounds to me like you&#8217;re using identification (&#8220;empathic&#8221;) descriptors which are complementary to my objectification (&#8220;doing&#8221;) descriptors. In both cases, however, empathy in the sense of emotive response is central to the porn consumption process, regardless of an &#8220;empathy/embodiment&#8221; scale.</p>
	   		</div>
   		</div>
